body:
This PR seriously degrades the quality of the tracing IMO. Taking my example in the linked issue

This PR prints:

```
DEBUG:    1+   >>>> dir $env:TEMP | ForEach-Object {
    if ((Get-Random -Maximum 15) -lt 1) {
        "Lucky file is $_"
        break
    }
}

DEBUG:    1+  dir $env:TEMP | ForEach-Object  >>>> {
    if ((Get-Random -Maximum 15) -lt 1) {
        "Lucky file is $_"
        break
    }
}

DEBUG:
DEBUG:
DEBUG:    1+  dir $env:TEMP | ForEach-Object  >>>> {
    if ((Get-Random -Maximum 15) -lt 1) {
        "Lucky file is $_"
        break
    }
}

DEBUG:
DEBUG:
Lucky file is C:\Users\jason\AppData\Local\Temp\38909067-9dd7-4538-ab8b-17c890f8c69c
DEBUG:
```

PowerShell Core pre-this PR:

```
DEBUG:    1+   >>>> dir $env:TEMP | ForEach-Object {

DEBUG:    1+  dir $env:TEMP | ForEach-Object  >>>> {

DEBUG:    2+     if ( >>>> (Get-Random -Maximum 15) -lt 1) {

DEBUG:    6+  >>>> }
DEBUG:    1+  dir $env:TEMP | ForEach-Object  >>>> {

DEBUG:    2+     if ( >>>> (Get-Random -Maximum 15) -lt 1) {

DEBUG:    3+          >>>> "Lucky file is $_"

Lucky file is C:\Users\jason\AppData\Local\Temp\418061a8-a7ad-4ed2-96dd-c55b3efca2de
DEBUG:    4+          >>>> break
```

Windows PowerShell 5.1 prints:

```
DEBUG:    1+  >>>> dir $env:TEMP | ForEach-Object {
DEBUG:    1+ dir $env:TEMP | ForEach-Object  >>>> {
DEBUG:    2+     if ( >>>> (Get-Random -Maximum 15) -lt 1) {
DEBUG:    6+  >>>> }
DEBUG:    1+ dir $env:TEMP | ForEach-Object  >>>> {
DEBUG:    2+     if ( >>>> (Get-Random -Maximum 15) -lt 1) {
DEBUG:    6+  >>>> }
DEBUG:    1+ dir $env:TEMP | ForEach-Object  >>>> {
DEBUG:    2+     if ( >>>> (Get-Random -Maximum 15) -lt 1) {
DEBUG:    3+          >>>> "Lucky file is $_"
Lucky file is 2f5d95a5-a611-4ec9-87c5-6db7eb198485
DEBUG:    4+          >>>> break
```
Of note - the proposed change never traces hitting line 2, 3, or 4 - it only traces hitting line 1.

It is also worth noting that PowerShell Core tracing (pre this PR) is more verbose (and worse in my opinion) with many blank lines that are not present in Windows PowerShell.

There are some performance concerns as well - splitting the entire script on `Environment.NewLine` will be very expensive for large scripts (and may not work as expected when a script uses CRLF when running on Mac/Linux).
